WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.305 align:middle line:90%


00:00:07.305 --> 00:00:09.230 align:middle line:10%
>> Hi, it's James here
from "Food Matters,"

00:00:09.230 --> 00:00:12.470 align:middle line:10%
and welcome to this interview
with Douglas Rushkoff.

00:00:12.470 --> 00:00:13.895 align:middle line:10%
Douglas is a media theorist.

00:00:13.895 --> 00:00:16.760 align:middle line:84%
He has a PhD, and he is
an author and founder

00:00:16.760 --> 00:00:19.490 align:middle line:84%
of the term, the
book, and the podcast

00:00:19.490 --> 00:00:22.070 align:middle line:84%
"Team Human," which
is about helping us

00:00:22.070 --> 00:00:25.790 align:middle line:84%
live in a more authentic life
in a time of great paradox

00:00:25.790 --> 00:00:28.460 align:middle line:84%
when we're more disconnected
than ever before

00:00:28.460 --> 00:00:31.640 align:middle line:84%
and more connected
than ever before.

00:00:31.640 --> 00:00:33.620 align:middle line:84%
He does this through
helping us understand

00:00:33.620 --> 00:00:36.560 align:middle line:84%
our colonialist past,
the Victorian era

00:00:36.560 --> 00:00:37.970 align:middle line:84%
and industrial
age and how that's

00:00:37.970 --> 00:00:40.730 align:middle line:84%
fed into the digital
revolution, and what

00:00:40.730 --> 00:00:43.040 align:middle line:84%
we can do to stave off
the anxiety and the lack

00:00:43.040 --> 00:00:46.970 align:middle line:84%
of self-worth that comes
with the modern era.

00:00:46.970 --> 00:00:48.750 align:middle line:90%
Douglas, how are you?

00:00:48.750 --> 00:00:49.880 align:middle line:90%
>> Hi, good to be with you.

00:00:49.880 --> 00:00:51.440 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, it's great.

00:00:51.440 --> 00:00:53.670 align:middle line:90%
I want to start early on.

00:00:53.670 --> 00:00:55.760 align:middle line:84%
And I think your
interpretation of this period

00:00:55.760 --> 00:00:57.500 align:middle line:90%
is really interesting.

00:00:57.500 --> 00:01:00.860 align:middle line:84%
As we colonized
the new world, we

00:01:00.860 --> 00:01:02.900 align:middle line:84%
were happily going
amongst our business,

00:01:02.900 --> 00:01:05.660 align:middle line:84%
but we were observed
in a very different way

00:01:05.660 --> 00:01:06.740 align:middle line:90%
by the indigenous people.

00:01:06.740 --> 00:01:08.180 align:middle line:90%
What was happening at that time?

00:01:08.180 --> 00:01:09.620 align:middle line:90%
>> Well, it's interesting.

00:01:09.620 --> 00:01:12.170 align:middle line:84%
I mean, most of us
know the conquistadors

00:01:12.170 --> 00:01:15.110 align:middle line:84%
and other colonizers
were not nice, right?

00:01:15.110 --> 00:01:18.200 align:middle line:84%
We were going, enslaving people,
and clear-cutting forests,

00:01:18.200 --> 00:01:20.540 align:middle line:84%
and really just destroying
nature, destroying people.

00:01:20.540 --> 00:01:22.610 align:middle line:90%
We were killing machines.

00:01:22.610 --> 00:01:26.220 align:middle line:84%
And I would have thought
that those people would

00:01:26.220 --> 00:01:29.070 align:middle line:84%
have just thought that
we're evil, you know?

00:01:29.070 --> 00:01:30.740 align:middle line:90%
Oh, white people are evil.

00:01:30.740 --> 00:01:34.220 align:middle line:90%
But they were such humanists.

00:01:34.220 --> 00:01:36.320 align:middle line:84%
They were such lovers
of humans and life

00:01:36.320 --> 00:01:38.870 align:middle line:90%
that they saw us as victims.

00:01:38.870 --> 00:01:42.710 align:middle line:84%
They thought that white people
had a disease that they called

00:01:42.710 --> 00:01:44.630 align:middle line:84%
"wetiko," and they
thought it was

00:01:44.630 --> 00:01:50.180 align:middle line:84%
a disease of the spirit that
led us to just destroy things

00:01:50.180 --> 00:01:53.420 align:middle line:84%
unnecessarily, this kind
of dominator mentality,

00:01:53.420 --> 00:01:55.530 align:middle line:90%
this domination of nature.

00:01:55.530 --> 00:01:59.630 align:middle line:90%
And I always appreciated that.

00:01:59.630 --> 00:02:02.900 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I'm trying to
hold onto that sensibility

00:02:02.900 --> 00:02:06.620 align:middle line:84%
that, no, people are
not intrinsically evil,

00:02:06.620 --> 00:02:12.140 align:middle line:84%
that we're in a system,
we're living on a game,

00:02:12.140 --> 00:02:18.020 align:middle line:84%
on a landscape that is
not natural, you know?

00:02:18.020 --> 00:02:20.600 align:middle line:84%
It's like setting up reality
as a game of musical chairs,

00:02:20.600 --> 00:02:23.045 align:middle line:84%
where there's not enough
chairs for everybody.

00:02:23.045 --> 00:02:24.920 align:middle line:84%
And then we think, oh,
well that's the world,

00:02:24.920 --> 00:02:27.380 align:middle line:84%
so we're all competing over
the chairs that there are.

00:02:27.380 --> 00:02:30.070 align:middle line:84%
But it's like, no, we could
just put two more chairs there,

00:02:30.070 --> 00:02:30.870 align:middle line:90%
you know?

00:02:30.870 --> 00:02:34.880 align:middle line:84%
And that's sort of
how I understand

00:02:34.880 --> 00:02:38.870 align:middle line:84%
central currency, and
corporatism, and capitalism,

00:02:38.870 --> 00:02:41.960 align:middle line:84%
that we had had
in the late Middle

00:02:41.960 --> 00:02:45.350 align:middle line:84%
Ages, the beginnings of
a peer-to-peer economy,

00:02:45.350 --> 00:02:47.720 align:middle line:84%
and we were using
market moneys that

00:02:47.720 --> 00:02:49.760 align:middle line:90%
expired by the end of the day.

00:02:49.760 --> 00:02:53.030 align:middle line:90%
And people were getting wealthy.

00:02:53.030 --> 00:02:55.490 align:middle line:84%
And the lords, the
aristocracy saw

00:02:55.490 --> 00:02:57.470 align:middle line:84%
that as the peasants
became the middle class,

00:02:57.470 --> 00:03:00.310 align:middle line:84%
the aristocracy got
relatively poorer.

00:03:00.310 --> 00:03:03.200 align:middle line:84%
So they made local
moneys illegal.

00:03:03.200 --> 00:03:05.240 align:middle line:84%
They made small
business illegal.

00:03:05.240 --> 00:03:07.760 align:middle line:84%
Now, you had to borrow money
from a central treasury

00:03:07.760 --> 00:03:10.758 align:middle line:84%
and interest, which meant
the economy had to grow.

00:03:10.758 --> 00:03:12.050 align:middle line:90%
You couldn't work for yourself.

00:03:12.050 --> 00:03:15.310 align:middle line:84%
You had to work for a chartered
monopoly or corporation,

00:03:15.310 --> 00:03:17.750 align:middle line:84%
sell your time
instead of your value.

00:03:17.750 --> 00:03:22.760 align:middle line:84%
So we ended up with this kind
of dehumanized view of people,

00:03:22.760 --> 00:03:26.330 align:middle line:84%
and this economy that
just by its very nature,

00:03:26.330 --> 00:03:30.260 align:middle line:84%
an economy that had to grow
in order to keep working.

00:03:30.260 --> 00:03:34.040 align:middle line:84%
So we started taking stuff,
just going to Africa,

00:03:34.040 --> 00:03:37.790 align:middle line:84%
and going to South America,
and just expanding by any means

00:03:37.790 --> 00:03:40.790 align:middle line:90%
necessary.

00:03:40.790 --> 00:03:42.590 align:middle line:84%
Really, as I see
it, that's the heart

00:03:42.590 --> 00:03:45.780 align:middle line:84%
of wetiko, of what
this disease is.

00:03:45.780 --> 00:03:52.640 align:middle line:84%
It's mistaking an operating
system, really, for reality.

00:03:52.640 --> 00:03:55.310 align:middle line:84%
And once you do that,
it's really hard

00:03:55.310 --> 00:03:57.340 align:middle line:90%
to see your way out of it.

00:03:57.340 --> 00:03:59.698 align:middle line:84%
>> How do you think that
the indigenous people,

00:03:59.698 --> 00:04:02.240 align:middle line:84%
especially the Indian Americans
I think you're talking about,

00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:06.520 align:middle line:84%
had such a positive
viewpoint on it all?

00:04:06.520 --> 00:04:08.620 align:middle line:84%
I mean, if anybody saw
that happening, they'd

00:04:08.620 --> 00:04:10.300 align:middle line:84%
be like, what crazy
people, and yet that

00:04:10.300 --> 00:04:12.730 align:middle line:84%
was so compassionate to think
that, oh, they're just unwell.

00:04:12.730 --> 00:04:13.840 align:middle line:90%
They'll get better one day.

00:04:13.840 --> 00:04:15.465 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, I don't know
if they thought--

00:04:15.465 --> 00:04:18.519 align:middle line:84%
I mean, they might have
thought it was a fatal disease.

00:04:18.519 --> 00:04:26.650 align:middle line:84%
I think it's because they look
into the eyes of another human

00:04:26.650 --> 00:04:32.210 align:middle line:84%
being, and they're able to see
that other person as a person,

00:04:32.210 --> 00:04:33.010 align:middle line:90%
you know?

00:04:33.010 --> 00:04:35.590 align:middle line:90%
And I think that's weird for us.

00:04:35.590 --> 00:04:40.180 align:middle line:84%
We tend-- "we" meaning, I
guess, white, Western Europeans,

00:04:40.180 --> 00:04:42.610 align:middle line:84%
and that whole
civilization, we tend

00:04:42.610 --> 00:04:46.270 align:middle line:84%
to see people who are
different from us as other.

00:04:46.270 --> 00:04:49.780 align:middle line:84%
We don't accept their
humanity as a given.

00:04:49.780 --> 00:04:53.740 align:middle line:84%
We see them first as an object,
then maybe as an animal,

00:04:53.740 --> 00:04:57.370 align:middle line:84%
and then, if they
really are close

00:04:57.370 --> 00:05:00.100 align:middle line:84%
enough to us and our
values, then, OK,

00:05:00.100 --> 00:05:02.110 align:middle line:90%
that's another person.

00:05:02.110 --> 00:05:11.890 align:middle line:84%
And I think that the indigenous
people had a heightened ability

00:05:11.890 --> 00:05:14.170 align:middle line:90%
to establish rapport.

00:05:14.170 --> 00:05:17.020 align:middle line:84%
That hadn't been
civilized out of them yet.

00:05:17.020 --> 00:05:20.380 align:middle line:84%
You know, making eye contact,
being part of an oral culture,

00:05:20.380 --> 00:05:22.420 align:middle line:84%
rather than a literate
culture or a television

00:05:22.420 --> 00:05:29.710 align:middle line:84%
culture means that you engage
with people by making eye

00:05:29.710 --> 00:05:32.380 align:middle line:84%
contact, syncing
up your breathing,

00:05:32.380 --> 00:05:34.660 align:middle line:84%
seeing if their pupils are
getting larger or smaller

00:05:34.660 --> 00:05:36.820 align:middle line:84%
as you talk to them, seeing
if your head is making

00:05:36.820 --> 00:05:38.740 align:middle line:90%
micro motions of agreement.

00:05:38.740 --> 00:05:42.400 align:middle line:84%
Then, the oxytocin gets
released in my bloodstream,

00:05:42.400 --> 00:05:44.470 align:middle line:84%
my mirror neurons
start flashing,

00:05:44.470 --> 00:05:50.710 align:middle line:84%
and it's a way of moving through
the world, of always optimized

00:05:50.710 --> 00:05:53.600 align:middle line:90%
for connection and rapport--

00:05:53.600 --> 00:05:54.400 align:middle line:90%
who is this?

00:05:54.400 --> 00:05:56.230 align:middle line:90%
How do we connect?

00:05:56.230 --> 00:05:58.540 align:middle line:84%
And if they do that,
even if they're

00:05:58.540 --> 00:06:00.940 align:middle line:84%
looking at a white Western
conquistadors who's

00:06:00.940 --> 00:06:04.052 align:middle line:84%
been told to take his sword
and start killing people,

00:06:04.052 --> 00:06:05.510 align:middle line:84%
they look in the
eyes and they see,

00:06:05.510 --> 00:06:07.180 align:middle line:84%
oh, there's this
human being there

00:06:07.180 --> 00:06:10.060 align:middle line:84%
that's being told to
go kill or to take,

00:06:10.060 --> 00:06:12.250 align:middle line:90%
but wow, they're in pain.

00:06:12.250 --> 00:06:14.140 align:middle line:90%
They're suffering.

00:06:14.140 --> 00:06:16.045 align:middle line:90%
And how do I reach that person?

00:06:16.045 --> 00:06:17.033 align:middle line:90%
>> It's beautiful.

00:06:17.033 --> 00:06:18.700 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I've certainly
experienced that.

00:06:18.700 --> 00:06:20.320 align:middle line:84%
When you go into
indigenous cultures,

00:06:20.320 --> 00:06:21.487 align:middle line:90%
they're much more connected.

00:06:21.487 --> 00:06:23.920 align:middle line:84%
They greet you regardless
of who you are,

00:06:23.920 --> 00:06:25.690 align:middle line:90%
or your title, or your worth.

00:06:25.690 --> 00:06:28.150 align:middle line:84%
They're like, wow,
hello, person.

00:06:28.150 --> 00:06:29.120 align:middle line:90%
Nice to see you.

00:06:29.120 --> 00:06:29.920 align:middle line:90%
Nice to see you.

00:06:29.920 --> 00:06:32.070 align:middle line:84%
>> I mean, I'm no
awakened being.

00:06:32.070 --> 00:06:32.870 align:middle line:90%
I'm really not.

00:06:32.870 --> 00:06:36.020 align:middle line:84%
But I remember I got
mugged like 10 years ago.

00:06:36.020 --> 00:06:39.460 align:middle line:84%
And I looked into the eyes of
the guy that was mugging me,

00:06:39.460 --> 00:06:40.930 align:middle line:90%
and he had this gun.

00:06:40.930 --> 00:06:45.250 align:middle line:84%
And I could tell
he was more afraid

00:06:45.250 --> 00:06:49.000 align:middle line:84%
than I was because,
well, first, he

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:51.700 align:middle line:84%
knew he was doing something
just awful and whatever,

00:06:51.700 --> 00:06:52.510 align:middle line:90%
but he also--

00:06:52.510 --> 00:06:55.380 align:middle line:84%
he's living in a
greater society, where

00:06:55.380 --> 00:06:59.710 align:middle line:84%
if a cop comes or I
scream in the wrong way,

00:06:59.710 --> 00:07:01.037 align:middle line:90%
his whole life is over.

00:07:01.037 --> 00:07:03.370 align:middle line:84%
He'll just be in jail the
rest of his life or something.

00:07:03.370 --> 00:07:08.200 align:middle line:84%
And just to see that, the
humanity of the person who's

00:07:08.200 --> 00:07:12.500 align:middle line:84%
coming after you or who's
threatening your life,

00:07:12.500 --> 00:07:18.740 align:middle line:84%
I can see how it's possible
that they were able to do that,

00:07:18.740 --> 00:07:20.180 align:middle line:90%
especially if you're in--

00:07:20.180 --> 00:07:23.750 align:middle line:84%
I mean, compared to
us, indigenous people

00:07:23.750 --> 00:07:27.950 align:middle line:84%
are in, like, an altered
state of consciousness.

00:07:27.950 --> 00:07:29.330 align:middle line:90%
We're in the simulation.

00:07:29.330 --> 00:07:31.550 align:middle line:90%
We're so removed from nature.

00:07:31.550 --> 00:07:37.730 align:middle line:84%
We are in a CG Disney movie
of the world, you know?

00:07:37.730 --> 00:07:41.720 align:middle line:84%
We're walking around like
Spock with our smartphones

00:07:41.720 --> 00:07:44.990 align:middle line:84%
like tricorders as if
we're on an alien planet.

00:07:44.990 --> 00:07:49.590 align:middle line:90%
That's how separate we are.

00:07:49.590 --> 00:07:54.050 align:middle line:10%
And I think that when
you're in and of the world,

00:07:54.050 --> 00:07:56.480 align:middle line:10%
when you're enjoying that
sort of home-field advantage

00:07:56.480 --> 00:07:59.150 align:middle line:10%
that you get as a
human being on Earth,

00:07:59.150 --> 00:08:05.210 align:middle line:10%
I think you start to see
the other humans more

00:08:05.210 --> 00:08:07.892 align:middle line:10%
gracefully than we might.

00:08:07.892 --> 00:08:08.740 align:middle line:90%
>> Beautiful.

00:08:08.740 --> 00:08:10.120 align:middle line:90%
Great observation.

00:08:10.120 --> 00:08:13.240 align:middle line:84%
I think where you eventually
end up with a lot of your work

00:08:13.240 --> 00:08:15.160 align:middle line:84%
is about this sort
of new digital era

00:08:15.160 --> 00:08:17.170 align:middle line:90%
and its impact on humanity.

00:08:17.170 --> 00:08:18.910 align:middle line:84%
But what I find
interesting is that you

00:08:18.910 --> 00:08:21.910 align:middle line:84%
use each of these important
stages of the growth

00:08:21.910 --> 00:08:24.670 align:middle line:84%
of the human species or the
domesticated white human

00:08:24.670 --> 00:08:29.710 align:middle line:84%
species, let's say, as analyzing
the values and the intention

00:08:29.710 --> 00:08:32.179 align:middle line:84%
behind each of those sort
of inflection points.

00:08:32.179 --> 00:08:36.039 align:middle line:84%
And so we just looked at
colonialism in a short way.

00:08:36.039 --> 00:08:37.750 align:middle line:84%
One of the other
great periods of time

00:08:37.750 --> 00:08:40.929 align:middle line:84%
which impacted us in many
ways was the industrial era.

00:08:40.929 --> 00:08:43.570 align:middle line:84%
And we became addicted
to these ideas of time,

00:08:43.570 --> 00:08:47.920 align:middle line:84%
of stamping in, stamping out,
of grades, and that infiltrated

00:08:47.920 --> 00:08:50.950 align:middle line:84%
so many areas of our life, in
particular schooling, which

00:08:50.950 --> 00:08:54.580 align:middle line:84%
I think has had a big
impact on who we've become.

00:08:54.580 --> 00:08:58.900 align:middle line:84%
How do you think that industrial
era impacted the schooling

00:08:58.900 --> 00:09:02.590 align:middle line:84%
system, for instance, and how
that sort of grow into sort

00:09:02.590 --> 00:09:04.585 align:middle line:90%
of impact us as a culture?

00:09:04.585 --> 00:09:09.370 align:middle line:90%


00:09:09.370 --> 00:09:11.820 align:middle line:90%
>> It's a big subject.

00:09:11.820 --> 00:09:17.090 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the hallmark
of industrialism,

00:09:17.090 --> 00:09:19.970 align:middle line:84%
really more than the steam
engine or anything else,

00:09:19.970 --> 00:09:21.800 align:middle line:90%
is the clock.

00:09:21.800 --> 00:09:23.820 align:middle line:84%
And it was it was
Mumford who said--

00:09:23.820 --> 00:09:28.220 align:middle line:84%
he wrote this great book
"Technics and Civilization--"

00:09:28.220 --> 00:09:30.920 align:middle line:84%
I think what he was
observing-- the power

00:09:30.920 --> 00:09:32.390 align:middle line:84%
of the clock in
the industrial age

00:09:32.390 --> 00:09:35.630 align:middle line:84%
is that before
the industrial age

00:09:35.630 --> 00:09:41.240 align:middle line:84%
people would create value
and exchange it, you know?

00:09:41.240 --> 00:09:43.610 align:middle line:84%
I'll make a candle
or make some shoes

00:09:43.610 --> 00:09:46.550 align:middle line:84%
and bring it to market and
exchange it with someone else.

00:09:46.550 --> 00:09:48.980 align:middle line:84%
When the industrial
age happened,

00:09:48.980 --> 00:09:52.550 align:middle line:84%
what it was really about
was disconnecting people

00:09:52.550 --> 00:09:54.410 align:middle line:90%
from the value they created.

00:09:54.410 --> 00:09:59.270 align:middle line:84%
So instead of me making a pair
of shoes and selling them,

00:09:59.270 --> 00:10:02.240 align:middle line:84%
now it's me going to
work at a factory,

00:10:02.240 --> 00:10:04.610 align:middle line:84%
nailing one nail into
the bottom of a shoe

00:10:04.610 --> 00:10:06.620 align:middle line:84%
and handing it over
to the next guy.

00:10:06.620 --> 00:10:11.150 align:middle line:84%
And instead of selling my
value, I'm selling my time.

00:10:11.150 --> 00:10:13.190 align:middle line:90%
I'm working by the hour.

00:10:13.190 --> 00:10:16.460 align:middle line:84%
They put the clock up on the
clock tower as if to say, look,

00:10:16.460 --> 00:10:17.570 align:middle line:90%
it's all fair.

00:10:17.570 --> 00:10:18.860 align:middle line:90%
An hour is an hour.

00:10:18.860 --> 00:10:20.180 align:middle line:90%
Isn't that just?

00:10:20.180 --> 00:10:23.390 align:middle line:84%
But what's intrinsically
unfair is that I'm not

00:10:23.390 --> 00:10:25.100 align:middle line:90%
allowed to create value.

00:10:25.100 --> 00:10:26.870 align:middle line:84%
I'm only allowed
to sell my time.

00:10:26.870 --> 00:10:30.000 align:middle line:84%
And now, 500 years
later, 600 years later,

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:31.850 align:middle line:84%
we see it as, well,
that's employment.

00:10:31.850 --> 00:10:32.650 align:middle line:90%
You just get a job.

00:10:32.650 --> 00:10:33.450 align:middle line:90%
That's what you do.

00:10:33.450 --> 00:10:34.610 align:middle line:90%
You work 40 hours a week.

00:10:34.610 --> 00:10:38.630 align:middle line:84%
It's like, no, but
that's sort of know

00:10:38.630 --> 00:10:41.750 align:middle line:90%
that "time is money" was born.

00:10:41.750 --> 00:10:43.050 align:middle line:90%
Because time was money.

00:10:43.050 --> 00:10:44.370 align:middle line:90%
It was all about time.

00:10:44.370 --> 00:10:46.760 align:middle line:84%
And then the only
metric that tends

00:10:46.760 --> 00:10:50.600 align:middle line:84%
to matter is the efficiency,
how much work can I get out

00:10:50.600 --> 00:10:52.560 align:middle line:90%
of someone in that hour?

00:10:52.560 --> 00:10:55.290 align:middle line:84%
How much value can I
extract in that hour?

00:10:55.290 --> 00:10:56.990 align:middle line:84%
So I want to increase
the efficiency.

00:10:56.990 --> 00:10:59.852 align:middle line:84%
And we had what was
called "Taylorism,"

00:10:59.852 --> 00:11:02.060 align:middle line:84%
which was a scientific
management school, where you'd

00:11:02.060 --> 00:11:03.653 align:middle line:84%
