it elevates your cortisol.

00:21:04.260 --> 00:21:09.090 align:middle line:84%
It keeps you in a kind of a
fight-or-flight state of mind

00:21:09.090 --> 00:21:10.830 align:middle line:90%
all the time.

00:21:10.830 --> 00:21:14.580 align:middle line:84%
So you can't rest
your eyes on anything.

00:21:14.580 --> 00:21:17.370 align:middle line:90%


00:21:17.370 --> 00:21:18.750 align:middle line:90%
I mean, you find no peace.

00:21:18.750 --> 00:21:19.890 align:middle line:90%
You find no rapport.

00:21:19.890 --> 00:21:21.360 align:middle line:90%
You can't establish connections.

00:21:21.360 --> 00:21:24.305 align:middle line:90%
It's like a Skype conversation.

00:21:24.305 --> 00:21:26.430 align:middle line:84%
It's interesting, you have
a conversation on Skype,

00:21:26.430 --> 00:21:29.370 align:middle line:84%
and the person on the
other end agrees with you.

00:21:29.370 --> 00:21:32.220 align:middle line:84%
But because you can't see
their pupils getting larger,

00:21:32.220 --> 00:21:34.290 align:middle line:84%
you can't see
their head nodding,

00:21:34.290 --> 00:21:37.020 align:middle line:84%
your body doesn't get
the sense of agreement.

00:21:37.020 --> 00:21:39.220 align:middle line:90%
Your mirror neurons don't fire.

00:21:39.220 --> 00:21:42.060 align:middle line:84%
The oxytocin doesn't
get transmitted.

00:21:42.060 --> 00:21:44.370 align:middle line:84%
And you don't blame the
technology for that.

00:21:44.370 --> 00:21:46.380 align:middle line:84%
You haven't evolved
to blame Skype.

00:21:46.380 --> 00:21:47.850 align:middle line:90%
You blame the other person.

00:21:47.850 --> 00:21:50.100 align:middle line:84%
You say that person's
not trustworthy.

00:21:50.100 --> 00:21:53.970 align:middle line:84%
And you trust humans
less because they're not

00:21:53.970 --> 00:21:56.520 align:middle line:90%
giving you--

00:21:56.520 --> 00:21:59.940 align:middle line:84%
they're not triggering this
sort of painstakingly evolved

00:21:59.940 --> 00:22:02.280 align:middle line:84%
social mechanisms that
we have, that we've

00:22:02.280 --> 00:22:05.370 align:middle line:84%
developed over 600,000
years of evolution

00:22:05.370 --> 00:22:09.900 align:middle line:84%
to bond with other people and
do the necessary collaboration

00:22:09.900 --> 00:22:12.360 align:middle line:90%
and social group formation.

00:22:12.360 --> 00:22:14.640 align:middle line:90%
So we get desocialized.

00:22:14.640 --> 00:22:17.370 align:middle line:90%
We can't think deeply.

00:22:17.370 --> 00:22:20.970 align:middle line:84%
I mean, Clifford Nass from
Stanford, who's now passed,

00:22:20.970 --> 00:22:23.430 align:middle line:84%
but he did all these
experiments with students, even

00:22:23.430 --> 00:22:26.490 align:middle line:84%
people who thought that
they were getting more done

00:22:26.490 --> 00:22:29.222 align:middle line:84%
while multitasking,
they invariably

00:22:29.222 --> 00:22:30.180 align:middle line:90%
were getting less done.

00:22:30.180 --> 00:22:31.680 align:middle line:84%
So they thought
they got more done.

00:22:31.680 --> 00:22:33.305 align:middle line:84%
They thought they
had better retention.

00:22:33.305 --> 00:22:35.400 align:middle line:84%
They thought they had
deeper understanding.

00:22:35.400 --> 00:22:37.650 align:middle line:84%
Invariably, when they
were multitasking,

00:22:37.650 --> 00:22:39.390 align:middle line:90%
they got less done.

00:22:39.390 --> 00:22:41.110 align:middle line:90%
They had less retention.

00:22:41.110 --> 00:22:43.020 align:middle line:84%
They had a more
shallow understanding

00:22:43.020 --> 00:22:45.930 align:middle line:90%
of what had just happened.

00:22:45.930 --> 00:22:47.560 align:middle line:90%
So what does that mean?

00:22:47.560 --> 00:22:53.550 align:middle line:84%
It means we're getting dumber,
or we're operating less

00:22:53.550 --> 00:22:58.740 align:middle line:84%
intelligently with less
thought, with less grounding,

00:22:58.740 --> 00:23:01.860 align:middle line:84%
and we're bringing less
of ourselves to bear.

00:23:01.860 --> 00:23:05.460 align:middle line:84%
So what happens, the thing
that I get most upset about,

00:23:05.460 --> 00:23:08.580 align:middle line:84%
is we end up with this kind
of profound reversal of figure

00:23:08.580 --> 00:23:11.980 align:middle line:90%
and ground, of user and used.

00:23:11.980 --> 00:23:15.760 align:middle line:84%
You are not the user
of your smartphone.

00:23:15.760 --> 00:23:18.390 align:middle line:84%
Your smartphone is
the user of you.

00:23:18.390 --> 00:23:22.740 align:middle line:84%
The apps on the phone are
designed to play the person.

00:23:22.740 --> 00:23:24.840 align:middle line:84%
You can go to
Stanford now and study

00:23:24.840 --> 00:23:27.270 align:middle line:84%
with BJ Fogg, who
has a lab called

00:23:27.270 --> 00:23:29.122 align:middle line:90%
"Captology Lab" at Stanford.

00:23:29.122 --> 00:23:31.080 align:middle line:84%
All the computer scientists
go through his lab.

00:23:31.080 --> 00:23:32.910 align:middle line:84%
And captology is
figuring out, how

00:23:32.910 --> 00:23:36.030 align:middle line:84%
do we use technology
to influence,

00:23:36.030 --> 00:23:39.520 align:middle line:90%
to design human behavior?

00:23:39.520 --> 00:23:43.260 align:middle line:84%
So we take all of the insights
of behavioral finance,

00:23:43.260 --> 00:23:46.230 align:middle line:84%
all of the algorithms from
Las Vegas slot machines,

00:23:46.230 --> 00:23:48.570 align:middle line:84%
and all of, now, the
learnings from the Internet

00:23:48.570 --> 00:23:51.600 align:middle line:84%
of Things and figure
out, how do we embed them

00:23:51.600 --> 00:23:55.830 align:middle line:84%
in apps to get people to
do what we want them to do?

00:23:55.830 --> 00:23:58.680 align:middle line:84%
So every time you swipe
on your smartphone,

00:23:58.680 --> 00:24:00.810 align:middle line:84%
it's getting smarter
about you, and you

00:24:00.810 --> 00:24:02.670 align:middle line:90%
are getting dumber about it.

00:24:02.670 --> 00:24:05.490 align:middle line:84%
And even if you want to find out
what the smartphone is doing,

00:24:05.490 --> 00:24:07.290 align:middle line:84%
the mechanisms,
they're protected

00:24:07.290 --> 00:24:09.660 align:middle line:84%
in black-box
architectures that have

00:24:09.660 --> 00:24:16.020 align:middle line:84%
proprietary, legal encryption
because these are trade secrets

00:24:16.020 --> 00:24:18.610 align:middle line:90%
that they won't even let us see.

00:24:18.610 --> 00:24:21.360 align:middle line:90%
So your phone is--

00:24:21.360 --> 00:24:23.190 align:middle line:84%
everything you do,
every agreement

00:24:23.190 --> 00:24:26.640 align:middle line:84%
you sign when you say,
yes, I agree, I consent,

00:24:26.640 --> 00:24:31.950 align:middle line:84%
is for them to mine everything
they can about every action you

00:24:31.950 --> 00:24:37.740 align:middle line:84%
take, every breath, every
swipe so that they can not only

00:24:37.740 --> 00:24:40.350 align:middle line:84%
predict what you
are likely to do,

00:24:40.350 --> 00:24:43.530 align:middle line:84%
but they can
attempt to force you

00:24:43.530 --> 00:24:48.240 align:middle line:84%
to behave true to your
statistical profile.

00:24:48.240 --> 00:24:49.710 align:middle line:90%
That's what Facebook is.

00:24:49.710 --> 00:24:51.600 align:middle line:84%
They use data from
your past to put you

00:24:51.600 --> 00:24:54.540 align:middle line:84%
in a statistical
bucket, and then

00:24:54.540 --> 00:24:56.400 align:middle line:84%
put stuff in your
news feed that gets

00:24:56.400 --> 00:24:59.110 align:middle line:84%
you to behave true to
your statistical bucket.

00:24:59.110 --> 00:25:01.980 align:middle line:84%
So if they know
with 80% accuracy

00:25:01.980 --> 00:25:04.950 align:middle line:84%
that you're going to go on
a diet in the next month,

00:25:04.950 --> 00:25:07.620 align:middle line:84%
your user feed, your
news feed's going

00:25:07.620 --> 00:25:10.320 align:middle line:84%
to start to have articles
in it like, oh, this is what

00:25:10.320 --> 00:25:11.820 align:middle line:90%
happens when you're too fat.

00:25:11.820 --> 00:25:13.620 align:middle line:84%
Or, look at a
person's blood stream

00:25:13.620 --> 00:25:17.160 align:middle line:84%
when it has you know
bad globules in it,

00:25:17.160 --> 00:25:21.330 align:middle line:84%
not just because they want you
to buy specific diet products

00:25:21.330 --> 00:25:25.950 align:middle line:84%
but because they want to
get that 80% of people

00:25:25.950 --> 00:25:29.100 align:middle line:84%
who are going to go on a
diet in your little group,

00:25:29.100 --> 00:25:32.460 align:middle line:84%
they want to get that
80 up to 90 or 95.

00:25:32.460 --> 00:25:38.010 align:middle line:84%
So they're just trying to
increase the predictability

00:25:38.010 --> 00:25:42.150 align:middle line:84%
of human behavior and
hone off the weird edges

00:25:42.150 --> 00:25:46.350 align:middle line:84%
of anomalous behavior
of unpredictable stuff.

00:25:46.350 --> 00:25:48.360 align:middle line:84%
But if you think about
it, if what we're doing

00:25:48.360 --> 00:25:51.510 align:middle line:84%
is taking the most powerful
technologies we have

00:25:51.510 --> 00:25:55.380 align:middle line:84%
and using them to try to get
the 20% of people who are going

00:25:55.380 --> 00:25:59.627 align:middle line:84%
to do creative weird things
and get that down to 10% or 5%,

00:25:59.627 --> 00:26:01.210 align:middle line:84%
and we're doing that
at a moment where

00:26:01.210 --> 00:26:03.790 align:middle line:84%
we need tremendous
amounts of innovation

00:26:03.790 --> 00:26:06.220 align:middle line:84%
in order to get ourselves
out of this corner

00:26:06.220 --> 00:26:08.410 align:middle line:84%
we've painted ourselves
into with climate

00:26:08.410 --> 00:26:10.480 align:middle line:84%
change and social
collapse, that's

00:26:10.480 --> 00:26:15.710 align:middle line:84%
a really non-winning strategy
for our human futures.

00:26:15.710 --> 00:26:18.610 align:middle line:84%
>> So are you in a in a
"boycott social media"

00:26:18.610 --> 00:26:19.540 align:middle line:90%
sort of camp then?

00:26:19.540 --> 00:26:20.770 align:middle line:90%
Or where do you sit on this?

00:26:20.770 --> 00:26:21.570 align:middle line:90%
I mean it's hard.

00:26:21.570 --> 00:26:25.360 align:middle line:84%
>> I don't see a use for
social media, you know?

00:26:25.360 --> 00:26:29.020 align:middle line:90%


00:26:29.020 --> 00:26:33.070 align:middle line:84%
You gotta look back at what
is the internet good for

00:26:33.070 --> 00:26:34.870 align:middle line:90%
or what could it be good for?

00:26:34.870 --> 00:26:38.590 align:middle line:84%
And what it could be good
for is connecting you

00:26:38.590 --> 00:26:43.300 align:middle line:84%
to people who have
something in common with you

00:26:43.300 --> 00:26:46.270 align:middle line:90%
that's non-local to you.

00:26:46.270 --> 00:26:48.490 align:middle line:84%
So you have some rare
disease, so there's

00:26:48.490 --> 00:26:50.320 align:middle line:84%
1,000 people around
the world, they

00:26:50.320 --> 00:26:52.270 align:middle line:90%
can connect on this network.

00:26:52.270 --> 00:26:55.150 align:middle line:90%
Or you've got some bizarre--

00:26:55.150 --> 00:26:56.740 align:middle line:84%
like, I'm interested
in, you know,

00:26:56.740 --> 00:26:58.270 align:middle line:84%
John Stewart Mills'
understanding

00:26:58.270 --> 00:27:01.040 align:middle line:84%
of the steady state
economy, who else is?

00:27:01.040 --> 00:27:02.590 align:middle line:84%
Oh, well, there's
some guy in Norway

00:27:02.590 --> 00:27:05.530 align:middle line:84%
and some other guy in
Japan, and we can then--

00:27:05.530 --> 00:27:10.030 align:middle line:84%
the places I have fun
online are rather--

00:27:10.030 --> 00:27:13.240 align:middle line:84%
I wouldn't say esoteric
but really particular

00:27:13.240 --> 00:27:14.230 align:middle line:90%
bulletin boards.

00:27:14.230 --> 00:27:16.840 align:middle line:84%
And they're going to
be old-style, HTML,

00:27:16.840 --> 00:27:20.650 align:middle line:84%
bulletin-board discussion
groups about weird things, even

00:27:20.650 --> 00:27:23.290 align:middle line:84%
if it's crazy antique
cars or whatever you like

00:27:23.290 --> 00:27:26.270 align:middle line:90%
or diseases of the pug dog.

00:27:26.270 --> 00:27:28.240 align:middle line:84%
Whatever it is
that's your thing,

00:27:28.240 --> 00:27:29.800 align:middle line:84%
you're going to
find that, and it's

00:27:29.800 --> 00:27:31.720 align:middle line:90%
a healthy set of connections.

00:27:31.720 --> 00:27:35.110 align:middle line:84%
But when it's substituting
for all of the real-world

00:27:35.110 --> 00:27:37.150 align:middle line:84%
connections that
you have, I mean,

00:27:37.150 --> 00:27:41.200 align:middle line:84%
the now stereotypical two girls
walking down the street texting

00:27:41.200 --> 00:27:44.590 align:middle line:84%
each other instead of
talking with each other,

00:27:44.590 --> 00:27:46.780 align:middle line:90%
that's where it's just--

00:27:46.780 --> 00:27:48.310 align:middle line:90%
that's where it's insane.

00:27:48.310 --> 00:27:52.520 align:middle line:84%
And you've got to understand,
of course, that Facebook is not

00:27:52.520 --> 00:27:53.320 align:middle line:90%
there--

00:27:53.320 --> 00:27:55.690 align:middle line:84%
these social media
companies are not there

00:27:55.690 --> 00:27:59.810 align:middle line:84%
to enhance your connection
with other people.

00:27:59.810 --> 00:28:02.560 align:middle line:84%
They are there to
monetize your social graph

00:28:02.560 --> 00:28:06.160 align:middle line:84%
and give value to
their shareholders.

00:28:06.160 --> 00:28:09.700 align:middle line:84%
So you could argue, well, I'm
a shareholder because I have

00:28:09.700 --> 00:28:12.760 align:middle line:84%
a retirement plan
with Facebook in it,

00:28:12.760 --> 00:28:17.170 align:middle line:84%
so I'll sacrifice my
children's mental health

00:28:17.170 --> 00:28:18.940 align:middle line:84%
so that my Facebook
stock goes up

00:28:18.940 --> 00:28:20.380 align:middle line:84%
so I can make
enough money to pay

00:28:20.380 --> 00:28:23.178 align:middle line:84%
for a psychiatrist for my
child who's cutting because she

00:28:23.178 --> 00:28:24.220 align:middle line:90%
doesn't have any friends.

00:28:24.220 --> 00:28:25.720 align:middle line:90%
It's like, wait a minute.

00:28:25.720 --> 00:28:27.130 align:middle line:90%
That's kind of ass backwards.

00:28:27.130 --> 00:28:29.830 align:middle line:90%


00:28:29.830 --> 00:28:34.600 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, I'm not like saying, don't
go on social media, oh my god.

00:28:34.600 --> 00:28:39.390 align:middle line:84%
But understand what it's for
before you use a platform.

00:28:39.390 --> 00:28:43.720 align:middle line:84%
Be in touch enough with
your emotional sensibilities

00:28:43.720 --> 00:28:45.970 align:middle line:84%
to think, how does
this platform make

00:28:45.970 --> 00:28:48.610 align:middle line:84%
me-- do I feel good when I'm
done with a Facebook session?

00:28:48.610 --> 00:28:50.980 align:middle line:84%
Do I feel great and
connected with others?

00:28:50.980 --> 00:28:53.350 align:middle line:90%
What's my heart rate after that?

00:28:53.350 --> 00:28:55.660 align:middle line:84%
What's my cortisol
levels after that?

00:28:55.660 --> 00:28:59.110 align:middle line:84%
Has the messaging I've gotten
been that the world is a place

00:28:59.110 --> 00:29:02.000 align:middle line:90%
that I want to connect with?

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:05.380 align:middle line:84%
Or is it teaching me that the
world's a weird and scary place

00:29:05.380 --> 00:29:07.480 align:middle line:90%
that I shouldn't go to?

00:29:07.480 --> 00:29:09.880 align:middle line:90%
So it's pretty basic.

00:29:09.880 --> 00:29:13.270 align:middle line:84%
It's why I used to argue
program or be programmed,

00:29:13.270 --> 00:29:16.300 align:middle line:84%
which didn't mean become
a programmer necessarily,

00:29:16.300 --> 00:29:19.360 align:middle line:84%
but understand what a
platform is programmed

00:29:19.360 --> 00:29:25.030 align:middle line:90%
for before you submit to it.

00:29:25.030 --> 00:29:29.230 align:middle line:84%
You know when you install
an app on your phone,

00:29:29.230 --> 00:29:31.300 align:middle line:84%
you think, how is
that going to affect

00:29:31.300 --> 00:29:32.443 align:middle line:90%
the ecosystem of my phone?

00:29:32.443 --> 00:29:33.860 align:middle line:84%
Is it going to use
a lot of power?

00:29:33.860 --> 00:29:34.840 align:middle line:90%
Is it GPS?

00:29:34.840 --> 00:29:36.490 align:middle line:90%
Is it this?

00:29:36.490 --> 00:29:39.100 align:middle line:84%
Think at least as much
about your organism

00:29:39.100 --> 00:29:42.410 align:middle line:84%
before you bring an
app into your life,

00:29:42.410 --> 00:29:45.010 align:middle line:84%
into your routine,
into what you're doing.

00:29:45.010 --> 00:29:46.602 align:middle line:84%
Just oh, the kids
are using WhatsApp.

00:29:46.602 --> 00:29:47.560 align:middle line:90%
They're using Snapchat.

00:29:47.560 --> 00:29:49.268 align:middle line:84%
They're using-- ah,
I gotta throw that on

00:29:49.268 --> 00:29:50.620 align:middle line:90%
and make that part of my life.

00:29:50.620 --> 00:29:52.330 align:middle line:90%
You don't.

00:29:52.330 --> 00:29:54.370 align:middle line:90%
You really don't.

00:29:54.370 --> 00:29:56.320 align:middle line:90%
And what are you missing out on?

00:29:56.320 --> 00:29:58.600 align:middle line:84%
What really are
you missing out on?

00:29:58.600 --> 00:30:01.190 align:middle line:90%


00:30:01.190 --> 00:30:05.075 align:middle line:84%
When you look at the opportunity
cost of the real world--

00:30:05.075 --> 00:30:08.030 align:middle line:90%


00:30:08.030 --> 00:30:08.830 align:middle line:90%
it's weird.

00:30:08.830 --> 00:30:11.920 align:middle line:90%
I was just watching the--

00:30:11.920 --> 00:30:13.930 align:middle line:84%
watching TV, and I
saw the commercial

00:30:13.930 --> 00:30:18.520 align:middle line:84%
for Disney's new "Lion
King" movie came on.

00:30:18.520 --> 00:30:21.280 align:middle line:84%
And they're calling it like a
live-action movie because it

00:30:21.280 --> 00:30:25.930 align:middle line:84%
looks real, but it's like made--
it's like a CG movie, where--

00:30:25.930 --> 00:30:28.490 align:middle line:90%
and you see this perfect--

00:30:28.490 --> 00:30:31.720 align:middle line:84%
it looks real, these lions
that look perfectly real

00:30:31.720 --> 00:30:34.600 align:middle line:84%
and this giant jungle that
the lions are going around in,

00:30:34.600 --> 00:30:36.070 align:middle line:90%
but I know they're not.

00:30:36.070 --> 00:30:38.830 align:middle line:84%
And I look really
carefully on my HD set,

00:30:38.830 --> 00:30:41.260 align:middle line:84%
and I could see the
lion is perfect.

00:30:41.260 --> 00:30:42.760 align:middle line:84%
A real lion-- when
you look at it

00:30:42.760 --> 00:30:45.970 align:middle line:84%
a documentary anyway
or at the zoo,

00:30:45.970 --> 00:30:48.160 align:middle line:84%
they've got wounds
and stuff, and rough

00:30:48.160 --> 00:30:51.100 align:middle line:84%
spots, and like callus on
their knees and things.

00:30:51.100 --> 00:30:52.960 align:middle line:90%
These lions are perfect.

00:30:52.960 --> 00:30:55.900 align:middle line:84%
And I'm thinking,
wow, here we are--

00:30:55.900 --> 00:30:57.700 align:middle line:84%
Disney, which is
part of the same kind

00:30:57.700 --> 00:31:00.010 align:middle line:84%
of giant industrial
complex that's

00:31:00.010 --> 00:31:04.090 align:middle line:84%
destroying the real jungle
and killing the actual lions

00:31:04.090 --> 00:31:07.510 align:middle line:84%
there is creating a
simulacrum, the simulation

00:31:07.510 --> 00:31:11.920 align:middle line:84%
of lions in the jungle that
now kids are going to grow up

00:31:11.920 --> 00:31:17.710 align:middle line:84%
and, in some ways, to them, that
is preferable to the real one.

00:31:17.710 --> 00:31:22.900 align:middle line:84%
And this is what those guys
like Adorno, and Benjamin,

00:31:22.900 --> 00:31:25.630 align:middle line:84%
and Baudrillard,
these people that we

00:31:25.630 --> 00:31:27.820 align:middle line:84%
all pooh-poohed in the
'80s and '90s saying,

